The Cripplestyle Benches
by Adrian King
If you travel from Alderholt to Cranborne, just before you reach
Cripplestyle, on the le, behind the hedgerow you will just
make out a small hill. It has the name King Barrow!
It is a popular desnaon for short walks, with a panoramic
view of the surrounding area when you reach the top!
At 324 King Barrow is the highest hill in the district. The
area consists of 23.62 acres of common land (registered
units CL 253 and CL 162). The hill itself is not a tumulus
but a natural mound. On a clear day it was at one me
possible to see the white clis of the Isle of Wight. I have
in the past seen the are
stacks of the oil renery at
Fawley. It was also possible
under the right condions
to see the top of Salisbury
Cathedral spire. But the
trees have grown so much
that the distant view is now
restricted. Clear cung
recently by the Cranborne Wild Heath Project has made new views possible.
On the Thursday following Whit Sunday the congregaon of Cripplestyle
Congregaonal Church processed to the top of the hill for an open-air service. During
that day, from sunrise to sunset a ag ew with the message Feed My Lambs. This
was to mark the anniversary of the opening of the Ebenezer Chapel in 1807.
Past forms of the name are, Kyngborghe 1404 Cecil, Kingbarowe e17 CecilMap,
Kingborrowe Heathe 1619 CH, King Barrow 1811 OS, King Barrowe Patch and Piece
1846 TA and King Barrow Hill 1869 Hutch. From the Old English meaning cyning king
and beorg barrow or hill. The current Ordnance Survey name is King Barrow.
The Local Defence Volunteers (LDVs) held exercises on King
Barrow. There is a legend that Uther the father of King Arthur is
buried on the hill. In 1940 when the Home Guard were dug-in, no
signicant nds were made.
Between Thursday 28
th
and Sunday 31
st
May 2020 a bench was
placed on the hill!
The seat part was painted red and rested on breeze blocks being
secured by a chain mounted on the centre of the seat and buried
in the ground below. There was an inscripon wrien on the seat.
By November 2020, the bench had been painted white and xed to
the breeze blocks without the need for the chain.
The inscripon that had been wrien on the top was now wrien
on a board secured to the front of the bench. There were now
three more poems wrien on the top of the bench.
But who could be responsible for thoughully placing this seat on
King Barrow? Research discovered that it was Marn Hollister, a
poet who lived on Cranborne Road between Biersweet and
Sunny Corner. His gate was adorned with dragons and dolphins.

Jean Bell said that there were spectacular iron dragons visible over
the hedge including a 3-headed one and one with babies. There are
two narrow panels on the le of the gate containing poetry.
Marn was not only responsible for the bench on King Barrow but
other benches around Cripplestyle, some of which had poetry
aached. There are two benches
alongside the path he created in the
strip of woodland between
Cripplestyle crossroads and the
Verwood turning now mostly
underwater!
Marn placed lengths of fallen
branches as edging to the path and drained water away from paths.
On King Barrow, by January 2021 three more poems had been wrien and
aached to a board on the back of the seat.
Over the next year and a half more boards were aached to the bench with more
poems - in all there were over twelve poems on the bench. But by 27
th
December
2022 the bench had deteriorated - the poems were becoming faded and
unreadable. The plywood panels were delaminang and by 6
th
February 2023
panels were beginning to drop o!
By the end of May 2023 all the panels had dropped o and later, some me in
June 2023 the bench was removed!
Marn, sadly died on 31
st
December 2022, but we sll in pictures have the legacy
of what his benches once looked like.
I have copies of all the poems if anybody is interested.
